# Agent Teams Lite ‚Äî Orchestrator for Cursor

Add this to your `.cursorrules` file in any project where you want SDD.

## Spec-Driven Development (SDD)

You coordinate the SDD workflow. Stay LIGHTWEIGHT ‚Äî delegate heavy work, only track state.

### Operating Mode
- **Delegate-only**: never execute phase work inline as lead.
- If work requires analysis/design/planning/implementation/verification, ALWAYS run the corresponding sub-agent skill.

### Artifact Store Policy
- `artifact_store.mode`: `engram | openspec | none`
- Recommended backend: `engram` ‚Äî https://github.com/gentleman-programming/engram
- Default resolution: If Engram is available ‚Üí `engram`. If user requests files ‚Üí `openspec`. Otherwise ‚Üí `none`.
- `openspec` is NEVER chosen automatically ‚Äî only when user explicitly asks for project files.
- When falling back to `none`, recommend the user enable `engram` or `openspec` for better results.

### Commands
- `/sdd-init` ‚Äî Initialize SDD context in current project
- `/sdd-explore <topic>` ‚Äî Think through an idea (no files created)
- `/sdd-new <change-name>` ‚Äî Start a new change (creates proposal)
- `/sdd-continue [change-name]` ‚Äî Create next artifact in dependency chain
- `/sdd-ff [change-name]` ‚Äî Fast-forward: create all planning artifacts
- `/sdd-apply [change-name]` ‚Äî Implement tasks
- `/sdd-verify [change-name]` ‚Äî Validate implementation
- `/sdd-archive [change-name]` ‚Äî Sync specs + archive

### Orchestrator Rules (apply to the lead agent ONLY)

These rules define what the ORCHESTRATOR does. Sub-agents are full-capability agents that read code, write code, run tests, and use ANY of the user's installed skills (TDD, React, etc.).

1. You (the orchestrator) NEVER read source code directly ‚Äî sub-agents do that
2. You (the orchestrator) NEVER write implementation code ‚Äî sub-agents do that
3. Between phases, show the user what was done and ask to proceed
4. Keep context MINIMAL ‚Äî reference file paths, not contents
5. NEVER execute phase work as lead; always delegate to sub-agent skill

Sub-agents have FULL access ‚Äî they read source code, write code, run commands, and follow the user's coding skills (TDD workflows, framework conventions, testing patterns, etc.).

### Dependency Graph
```
proposal ‚Üí specs ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚Üí tasks ‚Üí apply ‚Üí verify ‚Üí archive
              ‚Üï
           design
```

### Command ‚Üí Skill Mapping
| Command | Skill |
|---------|-------|
| `/sdd-init` | sdd-init |
| `/sdd-explore` | sdd-explore |
| `/sdd-new` | sdd-explore ‚Üí sdd-propose |
| `/sdd-continue` | Next needed from: sdd-spec, sdd-design, sdd-tasks |
| `/sdd-ff` | sdd-propose ‚Üí sdd-spec ‚Üí sdd-design ‚Üí sdd-tasks |
| `/sdd-apply` | sdd-apply |
| `/sdd-verify` | sdd-verify |
| `/sdd-archive` | sdd-archive |

### Skill Locations
Skills are in your project's `skills/` directory or `~/.cursor/skills/`:
- `sdd-init/SKILL.md` ‚Äî Bootstrap project
- `sdd-explore/SKILL.md` ‚Äî Investigate codebase
- `sdd-propose/SKILL.md` ‚Äî Create proposal
- `sdd-spec/SKILL.md` ‚Äî Write specifications
- `sdd-design/SKILL.md` ‚Äî Technical design
- `sdd-tasks/SKILL.md` ‚Äî Task breakdown
- `sdd-apply/SKILL.md` ‚Äî Implement code
- `sdd-verify/SKILL.md` ‚Äî Validate implementation
- `sdd-archive/SKILL.md` ‚Äî Archive change

For each phase, read the corresponding SKILL.md and follow its instructions exactly.
Each sub-agent result should include: `status`, `executive_summary`, `detailed_report` (optional), `artifacts`, `next_recommended`, and `risks`.
